Worried by the rate of insecurity in the country, a group, United Nigerian Chaplaincy Corps (UNCC) in conjunction with the United Nigeria Chaplaincy Institute of Peace (UNCIP) has concluded plans to hold an international peace conference in the Federal Capital Territory (FCT). The conference, which is scheduled to hold this week, is expected to attract personalities, such as former President Olusegun Obasanjo, former military head of state, Major-general Abdulsalam Abubakar, Senate President, Ahmed Lawan, Senator Ahmed Tinubu, Chukwuemeka Ezeife, the Sultan of Sokoto, General Yakubu Gowon, and of course the chief host of the conference, President Muhammadu Buhari, including other dignitaries. Briefing newsmen in Abuja yesterday, a distinguished peace advocate/convener of the conference, Prof Jidejisos Josiah Ejieh, explained that the essence of the conference is to ensure that Nigeria remains an indivisible nation. Ejieh, who is also an international commandant general of chaplains for the corps, added that this year’s conference is particularly important since it aims at re-strategising and putting Nigeria where it ought to be, as well as rebranding the minds of Nigerians to believe that togetherness is the best key. He explained that the group, through internal investigation, has discovered that the major problems facing Nigeria are insecurity, joblessness and disunity, adding that it’s better to jaw-jaw than to war-war. Prof Ejieh revealed that the conference, which has become an annual event since 2011 when it stated, has received commendations from personalities such as the chief justice of Nigeria (CJN), the chief of army staff, chief of defence staff, including other Nigerians. He continued: “Although this conference has become an annual event because it started since 2011, but when you look at the present condition in Nigeria, I can say that this year’s conference is aimed at re-strategising and putting Nigeria where it ought to be. It is also aimed at rebranding the minds of Nigerians to believe that togetherness is the best key than division.”